.SH "Building with Autotools"
.PP
.PP
.nf
$ \&./autogen\&.sh       # Generate a \&./configure script
$ \&./configure        # Generate a build system
$ make               # Run the actual build process
$ make check         # Run the test suite
$ sudo make install  # Install the library into the system (optional)
.fi
.PP

.PP
To compile optional modules (such as Schnorr signatures), you need to run \fR\&./configure\fP with additional flags (such as \fR--enable-module-schnorrsig\fP)\&. Run \fR\&./configure --help\fP to see the full list of available flags\&.
.SH "Building with CMake"
.PP
To maintain a pristine source tree, CMake encourages to perform an out-of-source build by using a separate dedicated build tree\&.
.SS "Building on POSIX systems"
.PP
.nf
$ cmake -B build              # Generate a build system in subdirectory "build"
$ cmake --build build         # Run the actual build process
$ ctest --test-dir build      # Run the test suite
$ sudo cmake --install build  # Install the library into the system (optional)
.fi
.PP

.PP
To compile optional modules (such as Schnorr signatures), you need to run \fRcmake\fP with additional flags (such as \fR-DSECP256K1_ENABLE_MODULE_SCHNORRSIG=ON\fP)\&. Run \fRcmake -\fBB\fP build -LH\fP or \fRccmake -\fBB\fP build\fP to see the full list of available flags\&.
.SS "Cross compiling"
To alleviate issues with cross compiling, preconfigured toolchain files are available in the \fRcmake\fP directory\&. For example, to cross compile for Windows: 
.PP
.nf
$ cmake -B build -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=cmake/x86_64-w64-mingw32\&.toolchain\&.cmake

.fi
.PP

.PP
To cross compile for Android with \fRNDK\fP (using NDK's toolchain file, and assuming the \fRANDROID_NDK_ROOT\fP environment variable has been set): 
.PP
.nf
$ cmake -B build -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE="${ANDROID_NDK_ROOT}/build/cmake/android\&.toolchain\&.cmake" -DANDROID_ABI=arm64-v8a -DANDROID_PLATFORM=28

.fi
.PP
.SS "Building on Windows"
The following example assumes Visual Studio 2022\&. Using clang-cl is recommended\&.

.PP
In "Developer Command Prompt for VS 2022": 
.PP
.nf
>cmake -B build -T ClangCL
>cmake --build build --config RelWithDebInfo

.fi
.PP
